                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout><q>A roman-letter, Latin inscription <rs type="execution" key="incised" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">incised</rs>, using a broad <rs type="execution" key="punched" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">punched</rs> line, in two lines reading vertically downwards... The inscription is set out somewhat unevenly but arranged to fill the available space.</q> The inscription fills the upper two-thirds of the stone face (Edwards 2007, 314). Macalister (1922b, 29) suggested ogham, but never saw strokes: <q>The SOLINVS stone at Clydai, I believe to have originally borne an Ogham, now broken away. I judge this from the appearance of the angle which would have been inscribed, for no trace of the scores remain</q>.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote><q>The inscription is in capitals. FI and LI (twice) are conjoined with small I's. In line 1 the first vertical of the N extends below the line. In line 2 D is reversed and the V's slightly curved... The vertical stroke of the reversed D projects slightly, but it is not a miniscule form...</q> (Edwards 2007, 314).
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
