        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="roman" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Latn">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down"/><persName><name>SO<hi rend="ligature">LI</hi>NI</name>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><w><hi rend="ligature">FI</hi><hi rend="ligature">LI</hi>VS</w><name>VEN<hi rend="inverted">D</hi>ONI</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>'of <foreign xml:lang="la">Solinus</foreign> son of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Vendonus</foreign>'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><q>The roman-letter, Latin inscription is an example of the simple 'X son of Y' formula, with names in the genitive and <hi rend="italic">filivs</hi> in the nominative case... <hi rend="italic">Solinus</hi> is a Latin name... VENDONI has often been regarded as Irish and is sometimes seen as a later form of the Irish name VENDOGNI... There are phonological problems, however, and it may be better to regard it as a spelling of the old Celtic name <hi rend="italic">Vindonius</hi> (from Celtic <hi rend="italic">*Windo-</hi>, 'white'), and therefore not specifically Irish, Welsh, or Celtic-Latin</q> (Edwards 2007, 314).</p>
            </div>
